  <div class="article-full hidden" id="article-rear-extension-cost-2025">
    <div class="article-back">
      <button onclick="showList()" class="btn-back-list">← Back to all guides</button>
    </div>
    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Extension Costs</span>
      <h1>Rear Extension Costs in the UK: What to Budget For in 2025</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>7 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>A rear extension is one of the most popular ways to add space and value to a UK property. Whether you're creating an open-plan kitchen-diner or adding a home office, understanding the cost before you appoint an architect or approach a contractor is essential to making the right decision.</p>

<h2>Rear extension cost per m²</h2>
<p>In 2025, a single-storey rear extension costs between £2,000 and £2,800 per m² for the structural build, before fit-out. At mid-range specification, a 20m² rear extension in the Midlands would cost roughly £40,000–£56,000 for the structural shell, with finishes, kitchen or utility fit-out, and professional fees adding further costs on top.</p>

<h2>How size affects cost</h2>
<p>Extension costs don't scale linearly. Smaller extensions often have a higher cost per m² because fixed costs — scaffolding, structural engineer fees, foundations, roof work, making good — are similar regardless of footprint. A 10m² extension might cost £2,600/m², while a 40m² extension could come in at £2,200/m² due to the spread of fixed costs.</p>

<h2>Single storey vs two storey</h2>
<p>Two-storey rear extensions cost less per m² (£1,800–£2,400/m²) than single-storey ones because you're doubling the floor area without doubling the foundation and roof costs. However, a two-storey extension typically requires planning permission where a single-storey may fall under Permitted Development rights, adding time and cost to the process.</p>

<h2>Regional cost differences</h2>
<p>Just as with renovation costs, location matters significantly. A rear extension in London will cost 25% more than the same extension in the North of England. For a 25m² rear extension at mid-range spec, that's the difference between roughly £55,000 in Manchester and £70,000 in London — before professional fees.</p>

<h2>What's included — and what isn't</h2>
<p>Most extension quotes cover the structural build: foundations, walls, roof, windows and doors, waterproofing, basic plaster finish. They typically exclude kitchen or bathroom fit-out, flooring, decoration, and external landscaping. Budget an additional 20–30% of the build cost for finishes and fit-out at mid-range specification.</p>

<h2>Professional fees and planning costs</h2>
<p>Architectural drawings, structural engineer fees, and planning application costs add a further 10–15% to the total. For a £60,000 extension, expect £6,000–£9,000 in professional fees. Always commission a structural engineer — not just an architect — before work begins.</p>

<h2>Recommended contingency</h2>
<p>Extensions routinely uncover drainage issues, unexpected foundation conditions, and services in inconvenient locations. A 15% contingency is the minimum advisable buffer, rising to 20% for older properties or complex sites.</p>

