    <div class="article-back">
      <button onclick="showList()" class="btn-back-list">← Back to all guides</button>
    </div>
    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Planning & Process</span>
      <h1>Hidden Costs of House Renovation: What Most Homeowners Miss</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>6 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>Even the most carefully planned renovation budgets have a habit of growing on site. Understanding where the hidden costs come from — and building them into your plan from the start — is the single biggest thing you can do to protect your budget.</p>

<h2>1. Structural surveys and investigations</h2>
<p>A standard homebuyer's survey won't tell you what's behind the walls or under the floors. A structural engineer's inspection, drain survey, and asbestos survey (required for properties built before 2000) can cost £500–£2,000 but will identify issues before your contractor does — when changes are expensive. These investigations are not optional on older properties.</p>

<h2>2. Services diversions</h2>
<p>Removing walls, extending the footprint, or opening up floor plans often means relocating electrical consumer units, soil pipes, gas supplies, and water mains. A single soil pipe diversion can cost £1,500–£3,000. If your project touches multiple services, budget £5,000–£15,000 for diversions alone.</p>

<h2>3. Planning and building regulations</h2>
<p>Permitted Development rules are frequently misunderstood. If your project falls outside PD rights — due to a previous extension, conservation area restrictions, or the type of work — you'll need full planning permission at £258 for householder applications. Building Regulations approval (required for almost all structural and services work) adds a further £400–£800 in fees, plus inspections throughout the build.</p>

<h2>4. Party wall agreements</h2>
<p>Any work that affects a shared wall — common in terraced and semi-detached properties — requires a Party Wall Agreement under the Party Wall Act 1996. If your neighbour requires their own surveyor, you pay their fees too. Budget £800–£2,500 per neighbour for surveyor costs.</p>

<h2>5. Temporary accommodation and storage</h2>
<p>A full renovation may make your property uninhabitable for weeks or months. Rental costs, storage for furniture, and the disruption of temporary living arrangements are costs that rarely appear in initial budgets but can easily add £5,000–£15,000 to a project.</p>

<h2>6. Snagging and remedial works</h2>
<p>Even good contractors produce snagging lists. Budget 1–3% of the total contract value for post-completion remedial works — tile alignment, door adjustments, paint touch-ups, and minor leaks. Chasing contractors back to site is time-consuming; having a retention fund in place gives you leverage.</p>

<h2>7. Landscaping and external works</h2>
<p>Extension projects frequently disturb gardens, driveways, and boundary walls. Reinstating these areas after construction can cost £3,000–£10,000 and is almost never included in a building contractor's scope. If you want a finished garden after the extension, budget separately for it from the start.</p>

      </div>
      <div class="article-cta">
        <div class="cta-inner">
          <p class="cta-eye">Free tool</p>
          <h3>Get an instant cost estimate</h3>
