    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Extension Costs</span>
      <h1>Loft Conversion Costs in the UK: A Complete 2025 Guide</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>7 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>A loft conversion is one of the most cost-effective ways to add a bedroom and bathroom to a UK home without extending the footprint. In 2025, a well-planned loft conversion offers some of the highest returns on investment of any home improvement — provided you understand the costs before you commit.</p>

<h2>Loft conversion cost overview</h2>
<p>Loft conversions cost between £1,500 and £2,500 per m² in 2025, depending on the type, specification and region. For a typical 30–40m² usable floor area, total build costs range from £45,000 to £100,000 before professional fees and fit-out.</p>

<h2>Types of loft conversion and their costs</h2>
<p><strong>Velux (roof light) conversion</strong> is the simplest and most affordable option, typically costing £20,000–£35,000. No dormer is added; instead, roof lights are installed to provide light and ventilation. Suitable for properties with adequate head height (at least 2.2m from floor joist to ridge beam).</p>

<p><strong>Dormer conversion</strong> is the most popular type, adding a box-like structure to the rear slope of the roof to increase headroom and floor area. Cost: £35,000–£60,000 for a standard single dormer. A full-width rear dormer can reach £55,000–£80,000.</p>

<p><strong>Hip-to-gable conversion</strong> is suited to semi-detached and detached properties with a hipped roof. The sloping hip end is replaced with a vertical gable, significantly increasing usable floor area. Cost: £40,000–£65,000.</p>

<p><strong>Mansard conversion</strong> is the most extensive type, raising the rear roof pitch to near-vertical and typically running the full width of the property. Costs £55,000–£90,000+ and almost always requires planning permission.</p>

<h2>Does a loft conversion need planning permission?</h2>
<p>Most loft conversions fall within Permitted Development rights, meaning no planning application is required. Exceptions include properties in conservation areas, listed buildings, and mansard conversions (which alter the roof profile significantly). Building Regulations approval is always required.</p>

<h2>What adds cost to a loft conversion</h2>
<p>Head height below 2.2m requires structural alterations to the floor joists and ridge beam, adding £5,000–£15,000. Adding an en suite bathroom adds £8,000–£15,000 depending on specification. London and South East projects typically run 15–25% above national average costs.</p>

<h2>Return on investment</h2>
<p>A well-executed loft conversion in the right location can add 15–20% to a property's market value. In London, this can represent £80,000–£150,000 of added value for a £60,000–£80,000 investment. Always verify with a local estate agent before committing.</p>

      </div>
