    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Planning & Process</span>
      <h1>How to Set a Realistic Renovation Budget: A Step-by-Step Guide</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>9 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>Most renovation budgets are set too low, too early, and without enough information. The result is a project that stalls on site, forces compromises in specification, or ends in a dispute with a contractor. This guide walks through how to set a renovation budget that is realistic, defensible, and resilient to surprises.</p>

<h2>Step 1: Establish your total available funds</h2>
<p>Before you look at cost data, establish your absolute ceiling. This is the maximum you can deploy — combining savings, remortgage proceeds, and any development finance. Do not start with a wish list and then try to find funding to match it. Start with the funding envelope and work backwards.</p>

<h2>Step 2: Ring-fence your contingency first</h2>
<p>A 15% contingency is non-negotiable for a full renovation. A 20% contingency is advisable for Victorian properties, projects involving structural changes, or extensions. This is not a buffer to be spent on upgrades — it exists solely to absorb unforeseen site conditions, design changes, and cost overruns. Set it aside before you allocate a single pound to the works.</p>

<h2>Step 3: Use cost data to establish a realistic range</h2>
<p>With your net budget (total funds minus contingency) established, use cost calculators and published benchmark data to assess what scope of work is achievable. At £600–£900/m² for a full renovation, a 85m² three-bedroom terrace in the Midlands should cost £51,000–£76,500 for the main works — before kitchen, bathrooms, or extensions.</p>

<h2>Step 4: Prioritise your scope</h2>
<p>List all the works you want to do and categorise them as essential (structural, safety, weathertightness), important (kitchen, bathrooms, heating), and desirable (landscaping, premium finishes, home technology). If your budget is tight, the essential and important categories are non-negotiable. Desirable items can be deferred to a second phase.</p>

<h2>Step 5: Get three quotes — and understand what they include</h2>
<p>Contractor quotes vary significantly in what they include. Always ask for an itemised breakdown and clarify what is excluded. Compare quotes on a like-for-like basis. The cheapest quote is rarely the best value if it excludes drainage work, waste disposal, or specialist trades.</p>

<h2>Step 6: Build a cash flow plan</h2>
<p>Construction projects require staged payments. Understand when payments fall due and ensure your cash flow can support them. Most contractors expect a mobilisation payment (5–10%), followed by monthly valuations. Retain 2.5–5% until snagging is complete.</p>

<h2>Step 7: Track costs in real time</h2>
<p>Use a simple spreadsheet to track every cost from day one: contractor valuations, direct purchases (tiles, sanitaryware, appliances), professional fees, and any variation orders. Review it weekly. Early visibility of budget drift allows you to make decisions before they become crises.</p>

