    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Extension Costs</span>
      <h1>Side Return Extensions: Costs, Planning & Everything You Need to Know</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>6 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>The side return extension is one of the most transformative projects available to owners of Victorian and Edwardian terraced houses. That narrow, underused strip of land running alongside the back of the house can — when properly opened up and incorporated — create a spectacular open-plan kitchen and dining space that fundamentally changes how you use your home.</p>

<h2>What is a side return extension?</h2>
<p>A side return extension fills in the narrow alleyway that runs between the rear of a terraced or semi-detached house and the boundary fence. Typically 2–3m wide and 4–8m long, it connects to the rear of the house to create a wider, brighter ground floor. Most commonly used to create a kitchen-diner, it can also work well as a utility room, home office or garden room.</p>

<h2>Side return extension costs in 2025</h2>
<p>Side return extensions cost between £2,200 and £3,000 per m² in 2025, making them slightly more expensive per m² than a standard rear extension. This premium reflects the complexity of working in a confined space, the need to carefully manage drainage and boundary conditions, and the typically higher specification finishes associated with kitchen-diner projects.</p>

<p>For a typical 15–20m² side return in London at mid-range spec, expect total costs of £45,000–£70,000 including fit-out, glazed roof or rooflights, and kitchen. Outside London, the same project would typically run £35,000–£55,000.</p>

<h2>Planning permission and Permitted Development</h2>
<p>Many side return extensions fall within Permitted Development rights, avoiding the need for a planning application. The key restrictions are: the extension cannot be wider than half the width of the original house (measured from the side boundary), cannot be higher than the eaves of the main roof, and cannot extend beyond the rear wall of the original house by more than 3m (4m for detached properties) under the standard PD limits. Properties in conservation areas typically require planning permission.</p>

<h2>Structural considerations</h2>
<p>Side return extensions involve opening up the original rear wall of the house over a significant length. This requires a structural engineer to design the steel beam (RSJ) that carries the load above the new opening. Beam costs and installation typically add £3,000–£6,000 to the project. Boundary walls are often shared with neighbours, which triggers Party Wall Act requirements.</p>

<h2>The glazed roof question</h2>
<p>One of the most important design decisions for a side return extension is the roof treatment. A fully glazed roof (structural glass or polycarbonate) maximises light but adds £8,000–£18,000 to the cost and creates thermal management challenges. A solid roof with rooflights (Velux-type units) is more affordable (£2,000–£5,000 for the rooflights) and better insulated, while still delivering excellent natural light. Many designers now recommend the latter for year-round comfort.</p>

      </div>
