    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Renovation Costs</span>
      <h1>Basic vs Luxury Renovation Spec: What's the Difference in Cost and Value?</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>7 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>Specification level is the single biggest variable in renovation costs after size and location. The difference between a basic and luxury specification on a three-bedroom house renovation can be £80,000–£120,000. Understanding what's included at each level — and which specification is appropriate for your property and goals — is critical to avoiding over-spending or under-investing.</p>

<h2>What specification level means in practice</h2>
<p>Specification refers to the quality and sourcing of materials and finishes: flooring, kitchen cabinetry, sanitaryware, tiles, ironmongery, windows, and appliances. It also affects the quality of workmanship you'll attract — premium tradespeople are more selective about the projects they work on and the materials they're asked to install.</p>

<h2>Basic specification (×0.85 of mid-range)</h2>
<p>Basic specification means functional, budget-conscious choices throughout: flat-pack kitchen cabinetry, ceramic floor tiles, standard sanitaryware and taps, UPVC windows, and trade-grade paint. Appropriate for buy-to-let properties, properties being prepared for sale in price-sensitive markets, or first projects with limited budgets. Can look very presentable when designed thoughtfully.</p>

<h2>Mid-range specification (the baseline)</h2>
<p>Mid-range represents good quality without excess. Rigid kitchen cabinetry (in-frame or shaker-style), porcelain floor tiles, branded sanitaryware (Grohe, Hansgrohe), composite worktops, timber or aluminium windows, and premium emulsion paint. The right level for most owner-occupied family homes and properties in areas with median to above-median values.</p>

<h2>High specification (×1.20 of mid-range)</h2>
<p>High spec means deliberately chosen materials with longevity and visual impact: hardwood kitchen units, stone worktops, designer sanitaryware, engineered oak flooring, Crittal-style steel windows, and bespoke joinery. Appropriate for premium residential properties, high-value areas, and owners planning to stay long-term.</p>

<h2>Luxury specification (×1.50 of mid-range)</h2>
<p>Luxury specification involves designer kitchens (Bulthaup, SieMatic, Smallbone), natural stone flooring, custom-designed bathrooms, heritage windows, handmade tiles, and extensive bespoke cabinetry. The cost premium is significant and the financial returns are rarely proportional except in prime London and South East markets.</p>

<h2>Matching specification to your property</h2>
<p>The fundamental rule is: never out-spec your neighbourhood. A luxury specification in a mid-range area adds cost without adding proportional value. Use local comparable sales to establish what buyers in your area have paid for renovated properties, and work backwards from that ceiling to set your specification budget.</p>

<h2>Getting the balance right</h2>
<p>Many successful renovations use a mixed specification strategy: mid-range on secondary spaces (bedrooms, hallways, utility rooms) and high spec on the rooms that sell houses — the kitchen and the master bathroom. This approach delivers the visual impact of a high-specification renovation without the full cost premium.</p>

