      <span class="article-cat">Planning & Process</span>
      <h1>How Long Does a House Renovation Take? A Realistic Timeline Guide</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>6 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>Renovation and extension projects take longer than almost everyone — including the contractors — initially expects. Understanding realistic timelines before you start helps you plan temporary accommodation, manage financial commitments, and avoid the frustration of an open-ended project.</p>

<h2>Pre-construction phase: longer than you think</h2>
<p>Before a contractor sets foot on site, you need: architectural drawings (4–8 weeks), structural engineer's calculations (2–4 weeks), building regulations submission and approval (4–8 weeks), planning permission if required (8–13 weeks), Party Wall Agreements (2–6 months if a surveyor is required), and contractor procurement including quotes and contract negotiation (4–8 weeks). In total, the pre-construction phase typically takes 4–9 months for a complex project. Projects that require planning permission routinely take 12 months from instruction to site start.</p>

<h2>Cosmetic renovation: 4–8 weeks</h2>
<p>A cosmetic refresh — new decoration, flooring, lighting and minor kitchen and bathroom updates — can typically be completed in 4–8 weeks by a small team. The main risk to timelines is material lead times: bespoke tiles, kitchen units and specialist flooring can take 6–12 weeks to procure, making early ordering critical.</p>

<h2>Full renovation: 12–24 weeks</h2>
<p>A full renovation of a 3-bedroom house — rewire, replumbing, new kitchen, bathrooms, windows and full redecoration — typically takes 12–20 weeks on site. Add 4 weeks contingency for a realistic 16–24 week programme. The critical path is usually: strip-out → first fix (structural, electrical, plumbing) → plasterwork → second fix (joinery, kitchen, bathrooms) → decoration → final fix (ironmongery, appliances, sanitaryware).</p>

<h2>Extension project: 16–28 weeks on site</h2>
<p>Extensions involve additional complexity: groundworks and foundations (2–4 weeks), structural frame and roof (4–6 weeks), weathertightness (2–4 weeks), and then the full internal fit-out sequence. A rear extension combined with an open-plan kitchen renovation typically takes 16–24 weeks on site at a minimum.</p>

<h2>Loft conversion: 8–14 weeks</h2>
<p>A standard dormer loft conversion takes 8–12 weeks on site for a competent specialist loft conversion contractor. The relatively fast programme reflects the specialist nature of the work — loft contractors move through the sequence efficiently because it's all they do.</p>

<h2>Common causes of delay</h2>
<p>The most frequent causes of programme delay are: late material deliveries (especially kitchens, tiles, and windows), variations instructed on site that require redesign, subcontractor availability gaps between trades, and discovery of unforeseen conditions (asbestos, hidden drainage, structural defects). Building these risks into your timeline expectations — rather than hoping they won't materialise — is the mark of an experienced project manager.</p>

