    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Extension Costs</span>
      <h1>Do You Need Planning Permission for an Extension? A UK Homeowner's Guide</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>8 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>One of the first questions homeowners ask when considering an extension is whether they'll need planning permission. The answer depends on the type of extension, its size, the property type, and where you live. Getting this wrong — starting work that required permission — can result in enforcement notices and costly remediation.</p>

<h2>What is Permitted Development?</h2>
<p>Permitted Development (PD) rights allow homeowners to carry out certain types of work without applying for planning permission. These rights are set by the central government but can be removed or restricted by Local Planning Authorities — for example, in conservation areas or on listed buildings. Always check with your local authority before assuming PD applies to your project.</p>

<h2>Single-storey rear extensions: PD limits</h2>
<p>Under standard PD rights (and the Larger Home Extension Scheme), single-storey rear extensions can extend up to 8m from the rear wall of a detached house, or 6m from a semi-detached or terraced house, provided the extension does not exceed 4m in height or half the width of the original house. The Larger Home Extension Scheme requires prior approval notification — it's not fully permitted but is a lighter-touch process than full planning.</p>

<h2>Two-storey rear extensions: generally require permission</h2>
<p>Two-storey rear extensions are permitted under PD only if they extend no more than 3m beyond the rear of the original house and are at least 7m from the rear boundary. In practice, most two-storey rear extensions require full planning permission because they fall outside these limits or have a material impact on neighbours' amenity.</p>

<h2>Side extensions</h2>
<p>Side extensions (including side returns that add above single storey height) generally require planning permission because they alter the visual character of the street scene. Single-storey side extensions may be permitted if they are less than half the width of the original house.</p>

<h2>Loft conversions</h2>
<p>Most loft conversions are permitted under PD rights provided the additional roof space does not exceed 40m³ (terraced houses) or 50m³ (detached and semi-detached). Dormers to the rear of the property are generally permitted; dormers visible from the highway or mansard-style conversions typically require permission.</p>

<h2>When you always need planning permission</h2>
<p>Planning permission is always required if: your property is in a conservation area or AONB, the property is listed, previous extensions have used up your PD allowance, or the proposed work is outside the standard PD limits. Building Regulations approval is always required for structural work, regardless of whether planning permission is needed.</p>

<h2>The cost of getting it wrong</h2>
<p>Carrying out unauthorised development can result in an enforcement notice requiring you to remove the work at your own cost. Mortgage lenders may refuse to lend against properties with unauthorised extensions, and the issue must be disclosed to buyers when you sell. The safest approach is always to check — a pre-application enquiry with your local planning authority typically costs £50–£150 and provides certainty.</p>

