    <div class="article-inner">
      <span class="article-cat">Planning & Process</span>
      <h1>How to Choose a Renovation Contractor: A UK Homeowner's Checklist</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>7 min read</span><span>UrbanBrief Toolbox</span></div>
      <div class="article-body">
        
<p>Choosing the wrong contractor is the single biggest risk in any renovation project. A bad appointment can cost you more than your entire contingency, drag a 12-week project into 18 months, and leave you with unresolved defects. The good news is that with the right procurement process, the risk is manageable.</p>

<h2>Start with referrals, not directories</h2>
<p>The most reliable route to a quality contractor is a personal referral from someone whose judgement you trust and whose project scope was similar to yours. Online directories and review platforms have their place but are more vulnerable to manipulation and less informative than a direct conversation with a previous client. Ask your architect or structural engineer — they work with contractors regularly and know who delivers.</p>

<h2>Ask to visit a live site or recent project</h2>
<p>Any contractor who is reluctant to let you visit a current or recently completed project should be treated with caution. Visiting a site tells you about organisation, cleanliness, and how the team works. Speaking to a previous client tells you about communication, budget management, and how problems were handled.</p>

<h2>Get three quotes — and make them comparable</h2>
<p>Issue the same detailed scope of work, specification, and drawings to all three contractors. This is the only way to compare quotes meaningfully. A quote 30% cheaper than the other two is not a bargain — it's a sign that something has been omitted or misunderstood. Ask every contractor to break their quote into trades and materials to identify where the differences lie.</p>

<h2>Check insurance and accreditations</h2>
<p>Any contractor working on your property must have Public Liability Insurance (minimum £1m, preferably £2m+) and Employers Liability Insurance if they have employees. Membership of a trade body (FMB, NFRC, NHBC) provides some assurance of minimum standards. For electrical and gas work, check NICEIC or Gas Safe registration respectively.</p>

<h2>Use a proper contract</h2>
<p>A JCT Minor Works contract, or at minimum a clearly drafted letter of appointment, protects both parties. It should specify: the scope of work, the contract sum, the programme (start and completion dates), payment schedule, variation procedure, retention terms, and dispute resolution mechanism. Do not start work on a handshake.</p>

<h2>Manage the contract, not just the builder</h2>
<p>The most common cause of contractor disputes is insufficient project management. If you're not going to appoint a project manager or clerk of works, you need to be on site regularly, attending site meetings, reviewing progress against programme, and approving variations in writing before they're carried out. A variation log — a running record of every change instructed after contract — prevents disputes at final account.</p>

<h2>Retention and defects period</h2>
<p>Retain 5% of the contract sum until practical completion and a further 2.5% through the defects liability period (typically 6–12 months). Release retention only when all snagging items have been resolved to your satisfaction. This gives you leverage to get defects fixed — once the final payment is made, your leverage disappears.</p>

